        "content": "<p>I have two specific terminology questions regarding bidirectional implication <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\iff</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.549em;vertical-align:-0.024em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟺</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span></span></span>.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Question 1</strong></p>\n<p>If <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟹</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\implies Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7073em;vertical-align:-0.024em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟹</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> is an implication,  <strong>what is the one-word name for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\iff Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7073em;vertical-align:-0.024em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟺</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span>?</strong></p>\n<p>Calling it a bidirectional implication is clumsy. And I can't really call it an iff statement.</p>\n<hr>\n<p><strong>Question 2</strong></p>\n<p>There are similarities between <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mtext>  </mtext><mo>⟺</mo><mtext>  </mtext><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\iff Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7073em;vertical-align:-0.024em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⟺</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A = B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>. They express equivalence, interchangeability. Whenever we see <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> we can replace it with a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span>, and vice-versa. Whenever we see <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span></span></span></span> we can replace it with a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span>, and vice-versa. </p>\n<p><strong>What is one-word label for these two relations?</strong> Is <strong>equivalence</strong> correct and precise?</p>",
        "id": 480996052,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730925183
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>biimplication is one word, right?</p>",
        "id": 480997230,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730925655
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>also (logical) equivalence should work</p>",
        "id": 480997283,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730925672
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if i may ask, what's wrong with calling it an iff statement?</p>",
        "id": 480997413,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730925717
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>btw, if you call something an equivalence between <code>A</code> and <code>B</code> in lean, people will assume you're talking about <code>Equiv A B</code>, not <code>A = B</code>. The first one bundles a bijection and inverse between the types <code>A</code> and <code>B</code>, the second one denotes true equality, something hard to prove and clunky to use in Lean. Mathlib uses an axiom stating that <code>Iff</code>s between <code>Prop</code>s are equivalent to equality between those props in lean.</p>",
        "id": 480998501,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730926159
    },
    {
        "content": "<blockquote>\n<p>what is the one-word name for P⟺Q</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>if and only if</p>",
        "id": 481003641,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1730928443
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"110049\">Mario Carneiro</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113489-new-members/topic/correct.20terminology.20regarding.20.3C.3D.3E/near/481003641\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<blockquote>\n<p>what is the one-word name for P⟺Q</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>if and only if</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's four words</p>",
        "id": 481003761,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrew Yang",
        "timestamp": 1730928489
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>that's the joke</p>",
        "id": 481003785,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1730928504
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but it's also kind of true, if you are in the right mental space then it's really not all that different from a single word</p>",
        "id": 481003832,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1730928530
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i guess I should have added - what's the word in common use, that most people will understand.</p>\n<p>I've never seen biimplication in the wild ever !</p>",
        "id": 481007167,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1730930126
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>the word is \"if and only if\"</p>",
        "id": 481007618,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1730930324
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>bi-implication is actually used as well, but it is less common</p>",
        "id": 481007810,
        "sender_full_name": "Mario Carneiro",
        "timestamp": 1730930405
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>\"biconditional\" is also used.</p>",
        "id": 481018128,
        "sender_full_name": "Dan Velleman",
        "timestamp": 1730936218
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi>Q</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P \\Rightarrow Q</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⇒</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8778em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">Q</span></span></span></span> can also be called a conditional statement.</p>",
